      "body": "There's no need to revert https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/commit/63091b79e70b8e230a122fa6fb3dac91c80638e7 as the PR didn't cause this.\n\nVersion 29.0 (before the PR):\n```\nsliv3r@sliv3r-tuxedo:~/BitcoinCore/bitcoin$ ./build/bin/bitcoind -datacarriersize=aaa\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Bitcoin Core version v29.0 (release build)\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Using the 'x86_shani(1way,2way)' SHA256 implementation\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Using RdSeed as an additional entropy source\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Using RdRand as an additional entropy source\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Default data directory /home/sliv3r/.bitcoin\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Using data directory /home/sliv3r/.bitcoin\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Config file: /home/sliv3r/.bitcoin/bitcoin.conf\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Config file arg: prune=\"5000\"\n2025-09-22T21:33:01Z Command-line arg: datacarriersize=\"aaa\"\n```\n\nChecking how we handle args, I saw that many numeric args accept strings without crashing.\nSee `-limitancestorcount` or `-bytespersigop` for example.\n\n`-dustrelayfee` on the ther side does have type handling:\n`Error: Invalid amount for -dustrelayfee=<amount>: 'aaa'`\n\nMaybe this is a issue worth checking to add assertions on args types.\nI think would be good if you modify the issue to make it generic and show that init args don't have type checks.",
